    "### Rate-of-Change Feature Interpretation\n",
    "\n",
    "Rate-of-change (difference) features capture how much each variable changes between consecutive time steps. Unlike raw values, these features focus on *movement* rather than absolute levels.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Key Observations\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Detection of sudden changes**  \n",
    "  Faults often manifest as abrupt shifts rather than gradual trends.  \n",
    "  Rate-of-change features help identify:\n",
    "  - sharp spikes or drops  \n",
    "  - sudden instability  \n",
    "  - unexpected deviations from normal behavior  \n",
    "\n",
    "- **Short-term dynamics captured**  \n",
    "  These features highlight rapid system responses that may not be visible in raw values, making them especially useful for detecting early-stage faults.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Directional insight**  \n",
    "  The sign of the change provides additional meaning:\n",
    "  - positive values → increasing trend  \n",
    "  - negative values → decreasing trend  \n",
    "  This helps distinguish between different types of abnormal behavior.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Reactor-specific consistency**  \n",
    "  By computing differences within each `reactor_id`, we ensure that changes are calculated relative to each reactor’s own history, avoiding cross-reactor distortion.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Expected missing values (NaNs)**  \n",
    "  The first observation for each reactor has no previous value, resulting in `NaN`.  \n",
    "  This is expected and should be handled during preprocessing.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Enhanced fault sensitivity**  \n",
