    "### Regime Deviation Feature Interpretation\n",
    "\n",
    "Regime deviation features measure how far a sensor reading is from the **expected average behavior under a given operating regime**.\n",
    "\n",
    "We compute:\n",
    "- **Regime mean** → average value of each variable within each operating regime (A or B)\n",
    "- **Deviation from regime mean** →  \n",
    "  `value - regime_mean`\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Key Observations\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Context-aware normalization**  \n",
    "  Instead of using global averages, deviations are calculated relative to the **operating regime**, allowing the model to distinguish:\n",
    "  - normal behavior in Regime A vs Regime B  \n",
    "  - true anomalies within each regime  \n",
    "\n",
    "- **Detection of abnormal behavior**  \n",
    "  Values close to **0** → normal for that regime  \n",
    "  Large positive/negative values → unusual behavior relative to expected conditions  \n",
    "\n",
    "- **Improved fault sensitivity**  \n",
    "  Faults may not always correspond to extreme absolute values, but rather:\n",
    "  - deviations from expected operating conditions  \n",
    "  - inefficiencies within a regime  \n",
    "\n",
    "- **Removes regime bias**  \n",
    "  Since Regime A and B have different baselines (as seen in EDA), this transformation:\n",
    "  - eliminates baseline shifts  \n",
    "  - allows fair comparison across regimes  \n",
    "\n",
    "- **Highlights subtle anomalies**  \n",
    "  Even small deviations can be meaningful if the system is typically stable under that regime.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Example Interpretation\n",
    "\n",
    "- Positive deviation → variable is **higher than expected** for that regime  \n",
    "- Negative deviation → variable is **lower than expected**  \n",
    "- Near zero → operating as expected  \n",
    "\n",
    "#### Conclusion\n",
    "\n",
    "Regime deviation features provide a **context-aware view of system behavior**, enabling the model to detect anomalies relative to operating conditions rather than absolute values. This is especially important in systems where different regimes naturally have different baselines."
   ]
